{{short description|Buddhist precepts kept on observance days and festivals}}
{{Buddhist term |title=Eight precepts |vi-Latn=bát quan trai |zh=八關齋/八關齋戒 |zh-Latn=bajie zhai, baguan zhai jie |ja-Latn=hakkansai, hassaikai |ko=八關會 |ko-Latn=p'algwan hoe |bo-Latn=bsny en gnas y an lag brgy ad |th=ศีลแปด |th-Latn=sin paet |si-Latn=aṭa sil}}
In Buddhism, the '''eight precepts''' ({{lang-sa|aṣṭāṇga-śīla or aṣṭā-sīla|italic=yes}}, {{lang-pi|aṭṭhaṅga-sīla or aṭṭha-sīla|italic=yes}}) is a list of precepts that are observed by lay devotees on observance days and festivals.

== Description ==
The first five of the eight precepts are similar to the [[five precepts]], that is, to refrain from killing living beings, stealing, wrong speech and to abstain from intoxicating drink or drugs,<ref name="BBC">{{cite web |title=Religions{{nowrap| –}} Buddhism: Theravada Buddhism |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/buddhism/subdivisions/theravada_1.shtml |publisher=[[BBC]] |accessdate=30 November 2018 |date=2 October 2002}}</ref> but the third precept is [[brahmacharya|abstinence of all sexual activity]] instead of refraining from sexual offenses.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tucci |first1=Giuseppe |last2=Kitagawa |first2=Joseph M. |title={{nowrap|Buddhism -}} Popular Religious Practices |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Buddhism/Popular-religious-practices |publisher=[[Encyclopedia Britannica]] |accessdate=30 November 2018 |date=27 April 2018}}</ref> The final three precepts are to abstain from eating at the wrong time (after midday); to abstain from entertainment such as dancing, singing, music, watching shows, as well as to abstain from wearing garlands, perfumes, cosmetics, and personal adornments; and to abstain from luxurious seats and beds.{{sfn |Keown |2004 |page=22}}{{sfn |Getz |2004 |p=673}}

To surmise, following anthropologist {{ill|Barend Terwiel's|de|Barend Jan Terwiel}} translation from [[Pali|Pāli]] language used in Thai ceremonies:
{{blockquote|
# "I undertake [to observe] the rule of abstinence from taking life
# I undertake [to observe] the rule of abstinence from taking what is not given
# I undertake [to observe] the rule of abstinence from unchastity
# I undertake (to observe) the rule of abstinence from false speech
# I undertake [to observe] the rule of abstinence from intoxicants which cause a careless frame of mind
# I undertake [to observe] the rule of abstinence from taking food at the wrong time
# I undertake [to observe] the rule of abstinence from dancing, music, visiting shows, flowers, make-up, the wearing of ornaments and decorations
# I undertake [to observe] the rule of abstinence from a tall, high sleeping place."{{sfn |Terwiel |2012 |p=191}}}}

In Thailand, when the eight precepts are taken, it is believed that if one of them is broken, they are all broken.{{sfn |Terwiel |2012 |p=201}} In some medieval Chinese texts, the order of the last three items is different, though the precepts are the same.{{sfn |McBride |2014 |loc=Buddhist Rituals}}

According to ethicist [[Damien Keown]], the eight precepts were derived from the regulations described in the ''[[Brahmajala Sutta]]'', an [[Early Buddhist Texts|Early Buddhist Text]].<!--28-30--> Since in this [[sutra|discourse]] the Buddha describes his own behavior, Keown argues that the eight precepts and several other moral doctrines in Buddhism are derived from the Buddha as a model figure.<!--31-->{{sfn |Keown |2016 |pp=28{{en dash}}31}}

== Practice ==
On regular [[uposatha|observance days]] ({{lang-sa|poṣadha|link=no}}, {{lang-pi|uposatha|link=no}}), Buddhist lay devotees often observe the eight precepts. In that context, the eight precepts are also called the '''uposatha vows''' (Sanskrit and {{lang-pi|upavāsa|italic=yes |link=no}}; {{lang-sa|poṣadhaśīla|italic=yes |link=no}}, {{lang-pi|uposatha-sīla|italic=yes |link=no}}).{{sfn |Keown |2004 |loc=Uposatha}}{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Aṣṭāṅgasamanvāgataṃ upavāsaṃ}} When laypeople stay in a Buddhist monastery<ref name="BBC" /> or go on a meditation retreat,{{sfn |Surinrut |Auamnoy |Sangwatanaroj|2017 |p=650}} they also observe the eight precepts often; they are also upheld during yearly festivals such as [[Vesak]].{{sfn |Vithararta |1990 |pp=230{{en dash}}1}}{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Baguan zhai}} Presently, the ''uposatha'' vows are mostly associated with Theravāda Buddhism in South and Southeast Asia,<ref name="BBC" /> but it was a widespread practice in China as well,{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Baguan zhai}} and is still practiced.{{sfn |Harvey |2000 |p=88}} In practice, in Theravāda traditions, the precepts are mostly observed by faithful devotees above 40 years of age.{{sfn |Harvey |2000 |p=87}} Since the eight precepts are often  observed for one day, they are also known as the '''one-day precepts'''.{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Upavāsa}} Sometimes a formula is recited confirming the observance for one day (and one night):

{{blockquote|"I undertake to observe in harmony during this day and this night these eight precepts that have been designed by the wisdom of the Buddha."{{sfn |Terwiel |2012 |p=191}}}}

Observance does not need to be temporary, however: some lay devotees choose to  undertake the eight precepts continuously to improve themselves in morality.{{sfn |Getz |2004 |p=673}} Furthermore, many nuns in Buddhist countries, such as the ''[[mae chi]]'' in Thailand or the ''[[dasa sil mata]]'' in Sri Lanka, observe the eight or ten precepts all the time as part of their way of life.<ref>{{cite web |via=Encyclopedia.com |title=Nuns: Buddhist Nuns |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/environment/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/nuns-buddhist-nuns |publisher=[[Thomson Gale]] |accessdate=1 December 2018 |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Religion |date=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |via=Encyclopedia.com |title=Nuns |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/nuns |publisher=[[Gale Group]] |accessdate=1 December 2018 |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Buddhism |date=2004}}</ref>

== Purpose ==
The [[Pali Canon|Pāli texts]] describe that one undertakes the eight precepts on the observance days following the example of the [[arhat|enlightened disciples of the Buddha]].{{sfn |Witanachchi |2003 |p=555}} The eight precepts are meant to give lay people an impression of what it means to live as a monastic,{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Aṣṭāṅgasamanvāgataṃ upavāsaṃ}} and the precepts "may function as the thin end of a wedge for attracting some to monastic life."{{sfn |Whitaker|Smith|2018 |loc=Ethics (sīla)}} People who are observing the eight precepts are sometimes also addressed differently.{{sfn |Terwiel |2012 |p=192}}{{sfn |Gombrich |1995 |p=78}} The objective of the eight precepts is different from the five in that they are less moral in nature, but more focused on developing [[samadhi|meditative concentration]], and preventing distractions.{{sfn |Harvey |2000 |p=87}} Indeed, in Sri Lanka, lay devotees observing the eight precepts are expected to spend much time and effort on meditation, focusing especially on [[Patikulamanasikara|meditation on the parts of the body]]. This is intended to develop detachment.{{sfn |Gombrich |1995 |pp=314, 329}}

Among the eight precepts, the third precept is about maintaining chastity. Buddhist tradition therefore requires lay people to be chaste on observance days,<!--201--> which is similar to the historical Indian tradition of being chaste on ''[[parvan (Indian history)|parvan]]'' days. As for the sixth rule, this means not having food after midday, in imitation of a [[Patimokkha#Pacittiya|nearly identical rule]] for monks. Fluids are allowed.{{sfn |Terwiel |2012 |pp=201{{en dash}}2}}{{sfn |Harvey |2000 |p=87}} The seventh precept is sometimes also interpreted to mean not wearing colorful clothes, which has led to a tradition for people to wear plain white when observing the eight precepts.{{sfn |Harvey |2000 |p=87}}{{sfn |Buswell |Lopez |2013 |loc=Ugraparipṛcchā}} This does not necessarily mean, however, that a Buddhist devotee dressed in white is observing the eight precepts all the time.{{sfn |Terwiel |2012 |p=187, n.16}} As for the eighth precept, not sitting or sleeping on luxurious seats or beds, this usually comes down to sleeping on a mat on the floor. Though not specified in the precepts themselves, in Thailand and China, people observing the precepts usually stay in the temple overnight. This is to prevent temptations at home which break the eight precepts, and helps foster the community effort in upholding the precepts.{{refn |See {{harvtxt |Terwiel |2012 |p=203}} and {{harvtxt |Harvey |2000 |p=87}}. Only Harvey mentions China, and the sitting.}}

== History ==
In 6th-century Korea, the eight precepts came to be associated with worship of [[Maitreya]], due to the work of Hyeryang, a Korean monk that wrote a tract about these matters.{{sfn |McBride |2014 |loc=Buddhist Rituals}} In the late 1800s in Sri Lanka, there was a renewed interest in the tradition of observing the eight precepts, during the time of the [[Buddhism in Sri Lanka#Buddhist revival|Buddhist revival]]. This was mostly because of the influence of [[Anagarika Dharmapala]], who observed the ten precepts (similar to the eight) continuously, maintaining a status between lay person and monk.{{sfn |Harvey |2013 |pp=378{{en dash}}9}} The interest was further fostered by campaigns emphasizing Buddhist religious practice on [[poya|traditional observance days]].{{sfn |Bloss |1987 |p=8}}

