'''Johannes Wilhelm Cornelius''' (September 27, 1863 &ndash; August 23, 1947) was a [[Germany|German]] [[Neo-Kantianism|neo-Kantian]] [[philosopher]].
==Biography== Born in [[Munich]], he originally studied [[mathematics]], [[physics]], and [[chemistry]], graduating with a [[Ph.D.]] in 1886, before turning to philosophy. In 1894, he [[habilitation|habilitated]] in philosophy and subsequently held a post in philosophy at the [[University of Munich]] (until 1903 as a ''[[Privatdozent]]''). In 1910, Cornelius moved as a full professor to the Akademie für Sozialwissenschaften, which four years later would become a department of the newly founded [[Goethe University Frankfurt|University of Frankfurt]]. Among his students in Frankfurt were [[Max Horkheimer]] and [[Theodor Adorno]]. He retired in 1928.
Cornelius died in 1947 in [[Gräfelfing]].
