{{infobox philosopher| | name = Ruth Lydia Saw | birth_date = {{birth date|1901|08|01|df=y}} | birth_place = Carshalton, Surrey | death_date = {{death date|1986|03|23|df=y}} | death_place = Carshalton, Surrey }}
'''Ruth Lydia Saw''' (1 August 1901 – 23 March 1986) was a British [[philosopher]] and [[aestheticist]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Osborne|first=Harold|title=PROFESSOR RUTH L. SAW|journal=British Journal of Aesthetics|year=1986|volume=26|issue=4|pages=307–308|url=http://bjaesthetics.oxfordjournals.org/content/26/4/307.extract|accessdate=19 February 2012|doi=10.1093/bjaesthetics/26.4.307}}</ref>
==Education and career== Ruth Saw attended the County School for Girls in Wallington, Surrey, followed in 1926 by [[Bedford College, London|Bedford College]], [[University of London]], where she studied under [[Susan Stebbing]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=S|title=Dictionary of Twentieth Century Philosophers|date=2005|publisher=Thoemmes|isbn=184371096X|page=925}}</ref> She accepted a position as lecturer in Philosophy at [[Smith College]] and remained there for several years. She then returned to England and was appointed to a Lecturership in Philosophy at Bedford College in 1939 and remained there for the rest of her career. She became Reader in Philosophy in 1946 and then Professor of Aesthetics from 1961–64. She was also Head of Department there from 1953 until her retirement in 1964.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Waithe|first1=Mary Ellen|title=A History of Women Philosophers|date=1995|publisher=Kluwer|location=Dordrecht|isbn=0792328086|pages=357–362}}</ref>
Saw's philosophical interests began with logic and philosophy of language, particularly on causal induction in [[William of Ockham|Ockham]]'s work.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Saw|first1=Ruth L.|title=William of Ockham on Terms, Propositions, Meaning|journal=Proceedings of the Aristotelian Society|date=1941|volume=42|pages=45–64|jstor=4544363}}</ref> This moved towards metaphysics, particularly Leibniz and Spinoza on whom she wrote full-length works. By the 1950s her interests lay with aesthetics. She was appointed Professor of Aesthetics in the 1961 and published three articles on the subject in the early 1960s.
Saw was a founding member of the [[British Society of Aesthetics]]. In 1963 she became Vice-President of the Society, and in 1968, on the death of Sir Herbert, she became President.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Meager|first1=R|title=Professor Ruth L. Saw|journal=British Journal of Aesthetics|date=1982|volume=22|issue=2|pages=99–102|doi=10.1093/bjaesthetics/22.2.99}}</ref> She began to play an active role in the [[Aristotelian Society]] from the mid- 1930s eventually to become the fifth woman to be elected President of the Society.<ref>{{cite book|title=Who Was Who|date=December 2007|chapter=SAW, Prof. Ruth Lydia|publisher=A & C Black|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U168872|accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> in 1965.
== Publications == *Saw, Ruth L. (1941). "William of Ockham on Terms, Propositions, Meaning". ''Proceedings of the Aristotelian Society'' 42:45 - 64. *Saw, Ruth L. (1951). ''The Vindication of Metaphysics''. London: Macmillan. *Saw, Ruth L. (1952). "Our knowledge of individuals". ''Proceedings of the Aristotelian Society'' 52:167-188. *Saw, Ruth L. (1954). ''Leibniz''. London: Penguin Books. *Saw, Ruth L. (1954). "Way to Wisdom: an Introduction to Philosophy. By Karl Jaspers. Translated by Ralph Manheim. (London: Gollancz, 1951, pp.&nbsp;208. Price 10s. 6d.)". ''Philosophy'' 29 (109):176-. *Saw, Ruth L. (1964). "E. F. Carritt". ''British Journal of Aesthetics'' 4 (1):3-6. *Saw, Ruth L. (1969). "Personal identity in Spinoza". ''Inquiry'' 12 (1-4):1 – 14. *Saw, Ruth L. (1973). "Aesthetics: An Introduction". ''Journal of Aesthetics and Art Criticism'' 31 (4):543-544.
